A memory leak occurs when memory that is no longer needed is not released back to the system. Memory leaks can occur accidentally in unmanaged languages by forgetting to delete memory that is no longer being used, or by forgetting to release it to the system, which could be by sending it to an incorrect address to get copied elsewhere in memory.

To detect a memory leak, it's important to track the amount of memory your program is using. There are several tools and techniques for this, and they can be more or less effective depending on the programming language, the memory management of the platform, etc.


